Henriette Stenius Wohlin

Making data frame:

aircrafts_ww2 <- read.csv("data/world_war_2_aircrafts.csv")

Cleaning data

Changing column names

colnames(aircrafts_ww2)[1] = "Aircraft_type"
colnames(aircrafts_ww2)[2] = "Aircraft_subtype"
colnames(aircrafts_ww2)[3] = "Aircraft_name"
colnames(aircrafts_ww2)[4] = "Year_service"
colnames(aircrafts_ww2)[5] = "Country"

Source: https://sparkbyexamples.com/r-programming/rename-column-in-r/

Problem: n/a, blank and 1 1930s in Year_service column. We need to fix that in order to change Year_ service column to a numeric one.

Removing n/a:

aircrafts_ww2$Year_service <- str_replace(aircrafts_ww2$Year_service, "s", "")

Source: https://sparkbyexamples.com/r-programming/r-str_replace-to-replace-matched-patterns-in-a-string/

Removing s:

aircrafts_ww2$Year_service <- str_replace(aircrafts_ww2$Year_service, "n/a", "")

Replacing blank with NA:

aircrafts_ww2[aircrafts_ww2 == ""] <- NA

Source: https://statisticsglobe.com/replace-blank-by-na-in-r

aircrafts_ww2$Country <- str_replace(aircrafts_ww2$Country, "Germany, Japan", "Japan")

Now I can change the Year_service column to a numeric one:

aircrafts_ww2$Year_service <- as.numeric(as.character(aircrafts_ww2$Year_service))

Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37707060/converting-data-frame-column-from-character-to-numeric

Visualizing every aircraft in dataset

First I would like to make a visualization of every aircraft in the data set to find out which has the highest count.

Let’s try to count every aircraft first:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  select(Aircraft_type) %>% 
  count(Aircraft_type, sort = TRUE)
##                                  Aircraft_type   n
## 1                                   Prototypes 292
## 2                   Bomber and Attack aircraft 189
## 3               Transport and Utility aircraft 178
## 4                                     Trainers 151
## 5                             Fighter aircraft 147
## 6                                    Seaplanes 127
## 7                                     Research  32
## 8  Strategic and Photo-reconnaissance aircraft  30
## 9                           Rockets and Drones  15
## 10                                  Rotorcraft   8
## 11                                      Blimps   4
## 12                               Misc research   3

“Strategic and photo-reconnaissance aircraft” is a long name so I am changing it to “Strat. and Photo-recon. aircraft”:

aircrafts_ww2$Aircraft_type <- gsub("Strategic and Photo-reconnaissance aircraft", "Strat. and Photo-recon. aircraft", aircrafts_ww2$Aircraft_type)

Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50615116/renaming-character-variables-in-a-column-in-data-frame-r

Now I can visualize how many of the different types of aircrafts that there are in the data set:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  select(Aircraft_type) %>% 
  count(Aircraft_type, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(Aircraft_type = fct_reorder(Aircraft_type, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = Aircraft_type, fill=Aircraft_type)) +
  geom_col() + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Total number of Aircrafts", 
       y = "Aircraft type",
       x = "Number of aircrafts") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0,300,20)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Source for fct_reorder code: https://r-graph-gallery.com/267-reorder-a-variable-in-ggplot2.html

From this data we can see that Prototypes have the highest count by a lot.

However, on the Wikipedia page it says that Prototypes aircrafts was intended to enter service but did not. Research Aircraft was intended to prove a concept or an idea but was also not suitable for military service. Trainers also did not enter active combat.

I would then like to make some visualization of of the aircrafts actually used during the war.

Visualizing aircrafts used in WW2

Let us start by counting the aircrafts once more.

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  filter(Aircraft_type %in% c("Fighter aircraft", "Bomber and Attack aircraft", "Seaplanes", "Transport and Utility aircraft", "Rotorcraft", "Blimps", "Rockets and Drones", "Strat. and Photo-recon aircraft","Trainers")) %>% 
  count(Aircraft_type, sort = TRUE)
##                    Aircraft_type   n
## 1     Bomber and Attack aircraft 189
## 2 Transport and Utility aircraft 178
## 3                       Trainers 151
## 4               Fighter aircraft 147
## 5                      Seaplanes 127
## 6             Rockets and Drones  15
## 7                     Rotorcraft   8
## 8                         Blimps   4

Now let us try to visualize it:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  filter(Aircraft_type %in% c("Fighter aircraft", "Bomber and Attack aircraft", "Seaplanes", "Transport and Utility aircraft", "Rotorcraft", "Blimps", "Rockets and Drones", "Strat. and Photo-recon. aircraft","Trainers")) %>% 
  count(Aircraft_type, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(Aircraft_type = fct_reorder(Aircraft_type, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = Aircraft_type, fill=Aircraft_type)) +
  geom_col() + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Total number of Aircrafts that entered active combat in WW2", 
       y = "Aircraft type",
       x = "Number of aircrafts") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0,200,10)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Bomber and Attack aircrafts looks like to be the highest with Transport and Utility aircrafts close behind. Rockets & Drones, Rotercrafts and Blimps are the lowest.

Visualizing aircrafts not in active service during WW2

Now let us look at aircrafts not in service during the war. I repeat what I did before:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%

##   Aircraft_type   n
## 1    Prototypes 292
## 2      Research  32
## 3 Misc research   3
aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  filter(Aircraft_type %in% c("Prototypes", "Research", "Misc research")) %>% 
  count(Aircraft_type, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(Aircraft_type = fct_reorder(Aircraft_type, n)) %>%

From this we can again see that prototypes has a high count.

Aircrafts and origin of Country

Now I would like to look at which country produced the most aircrafts.

First we can try for every aircraft:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  drop_na(Country) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = fct_rev(fct_infreq(Country)))) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Aircraft_type), alpha = 5) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Aircraft type by Country of origin",
       y = "Number of aircrafts",
       x = "Country") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0,300,20))

From this we can see that the US has the most types of aircraft followed by UK, then Germany, Japan, France, Italy, USSR and so on.

I would like to compare the biggest participants of aircrafts in World War 2, so I will sort it even more:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  filter(Country %in% c ("US", "UK", "Germany", "Japan", "France", "USSR", "Italy")) %>% 
  drop_na(Country) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = fct_rev(fct_infreq(Country)))) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Aircraft_type), alpha = 5) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Aircraft type by Country of origin",
       y = "Number of aircrafts",
       x = "Country") +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0,300,10)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

However, this is very hard to make sense of so I will split the aircrafts again between if it was in service during the war or not.

1940 is the highest year that aircrafts had their first flight, followed by 1942 and 1941.

Now let us try to visualize it as we have done before with every aircraft:

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  drop_na(Year_service) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year_service)) +

       y = "Number of aircrafts",

    scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1913,1945,1)) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8))

To make it easier I would like to split the years between the interwar period from 1919-1938 and World War 2 1939-1945.

Interwar period (1919-1938):

aircrafts_ww2 %>%
  drop_na(Year_service) %>% 
  filter(Year_service %in% c("1919","1920", "1921", "1922", "1923", "1924", "1925", "1926", "1926", "1927", "1928", "1929", "1930","1931","1932","1933", "1934","1935", "1936", "1937","1938")) %>%

  ggplot(aes(x = Year_service)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Aircraft_type)) +
  labs(title = "Aircrafts that entered active combat in WW2 and Year of service (1919-1938)",
       y = "Number of aircrafts",
       x = "Entered service (Year)") +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0,70,5)) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1919,1938,1)) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

From 1940-1942 there definitely was more aircrafts that entered service compared to the other years. As it got closer to World War 2 there was more aircrafts made.
